    "text": "Yes — a heart pounding hard on a steep climb and settling as soon as you stop is your cardiovascular system doing exactly what climbs demand; effort-proportional pounding that resolves with rest is the benign version, unlike palpitations that arrive at rest or an irregular flutter, which would be doctor territory. What your data does say is that yesterday was big: a training load of 20.1 against a weekly strain average around 12.7, and your HRV at 45 ms matches its recent 45 ms average but the week reads on the suppressed side. I don't get a recovery score from this source, so reading those signals directly: walk today, but keep it flat and conversational rather than repeating the climb, and let the legs vote on pace. Save the steep route for later in the week once the load settles.",
